<br>
51 &quot;I am the living bread that came down out of heaven; if anyone eats of this bread, he will live forever; and the bread also which I will give for the life of the world is My flesh.&quot;  <br>
<br>
52 Then the Jews began to argue with one another, saying, &quot;How can this man give us His flesh to eat?&quot; <br>
53 So Jesus said to them, &quot;Truly, truly, I say to you, unless you eat the flesh of the Son of Man and drink His blood, you have no life in yourselves. <br>
54 &quot;He who eats My flesh and drinks My blood has eternal life, and I will raise him up on the last day. <br>
55 &quot;For My flesh is true food, and My blood is true drink. <br>
56 &quot;He who eats My flesh and drinks My blood abides in Me, and I in him. <br>
57 &quot;As the living Father sent Me, and I live because of the Father, so he who eats Me, he also will live because of Me. <br>
58 &quot;This is the bread which came down out of heaven; not as the fathers ate and died; he who eats this bread will live forever.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Many disciples even leave Christ over this, and when they leave, Christ *doesn't* say &quot;I'm just being symbolic, come back guys!&quot; - instead, he *repeats* his words, and then asks the apostles if they are going to leave to. This is difficult text from me to read and accept literally, but when I apply the &quot;grammatical, historical&quot; method of interpretation, I am left with little choice. John 6:55 especially - where Christ is making it the point that he's NOT being symbolic.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't know how you get from John 6:55 that Jesus is &quot;NOT being symbolic.&quot;  It is a metaphor.  This is evident to me from vs. 63.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>John 6:63<br>
63 &quot;It is the Spirit who gives life; the flesh profits nothing; the words that I have spoken to you are spirit and are life.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The issue is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>abiding</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> in Christ.  Do you abide in Christ by means of communion or by means of the Spirit?  Maybe a survey of John's use of &quot;abide&quot; in 1 John would be of help, if you haven't considered it already.<br>
<br>
As for the &quot;grammatical, historical&quot; method -- I try to interpret the Bible sensibly (or so I think).  I have decided that some <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>trumpet</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the &quot;grammatical, historical&quot; method as a justification of bizarre theology. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=esdras>esdras</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator<br>Sir Esdras, Brewmeister <br>of the Great White North</span><br>  Posts: 193<br> <font color=#B87333>(6/26/03 10:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19.topic&index=4>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www3.sympatico.ca/gsmorgan/images/ADPY005.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Eucharist</span><hr size=1> I don't think verse 63 indicates that the previous verses are metaphorical.  Let's continue where you left off at verse 58.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>John 6:59-71<br>
59 This he said in the synagogue, as he taught at Caper'na-um.<br>
60 Many of his disciples, when they heard it, said, &quot;This is a hard saying; who can listen to it?&quot;<br>
61 But Jesus, knowing in himself that his disciples murmured at it, said to them, &quot;Do you take offense at this?<br>
62 Then what if you were to see the Son of man ascending where he was before?<br>
63 It is the spirit that gives life, the flesh is of no avail; the words that I have spoken to you are spirit and life.<br>
64 But there are some of you that do not believe.&quot; For Jesus knew from the first who those were that did not believe, and who it was that would betray him.<br>
65 And he said, &quot;This is why I told you that no one can come to me unless it is granted him by the Father.&quot;<br>
66 After this many of his disciples drew back and no longer went about with him.<br>
67 Jesus said to the twelve, &quot;Do you also wish to go away?&quot;<br>
68 Simon Peter answered him, &quot;Lord, to whom shall we go? You have the words of eternal life;<br>
69 and we have believed, and have come to know, that you are the Holy One of God.&quot;<br>
70 Jesus answered them, &quot;Did I not choose you, the twelve, and one of you is a devil?&quot;<br>
71 He spoke of Judas the son of Simon Iscariot, for he, one of the twelve, was to betray him.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
In verse 60 we have the followers reacting to the statement, finding it hard to comprehend, and to be fair, rightly so.<br>
In verse 61, Jesus asks them outright if they have a problem with what He said.<br>
Verse 62 has Jesus describe another thing that is true that will also be a miraculous thing that He will do... ascend into Heaven.  Jesus did this.  Really did this.  Still no metaphor.<br>
Verse 63 - the one you quote - isn't saying that he's speaking metaphically.  Look at a more modern translation - &quot;It is the Spirit who gives eternal life. Human effort accomplishes nothing. And the very words I have spoken to you are spirit and life.&quot; NLT.  Essentially saying salvation is by faith.  He's comparing having faith in the saving spirit with faith in His words, which are hard.<br>
This is evidenced as He goes onto verse 64, saying quite clearly that there will be those who won't believe.<br>
Verse 65 is simply stating that no one actually can believe without it being granted by the Father.  God's grace must enable them to have faith.  A fairly popular verse with those of the Reformed persuasion, but not irreconcilable with Catholic teaching.<br>
Verses 66 to 71 simply state that many left Him that day, except for the 12, one of whom would betray Him.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As for the &quot;grammatical, historical&quot; method -- I try to interpret the Bible sensibly (or so I think). I have decided that some trumpet the &quot;grammatical, historical&quot; method as a justification of bizarre theology.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ironically I had a rather interesting debate with an independent Baptist who said that the Catholics screw up the interpretation of the Bible by looking at everything allegorically.  Now, according to this, we mess it up by taking a part of it grammatically/historically.  Ah, well.  Can't win. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
<br>
