Bizarre theology, for a literal reading of Our Lord's words at John 6:55?<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Epistle of St. Ignatius of Antioch to the Smyrnaeans</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>6:1Let no man be deceived. Even the heavenly things, and the glory of the angels, and the principalities, both visible and invisible, if they believe not on the blood of Christ, for them also is there condemnation. Let him who receiveth it, receive it in reality. Let not high place puff up any man. For the whole matter is faith and love, to which there is nothing preferable. <br>
6:2 Consider those who hold heretical opinions with regard to the grace of Jesus Christ which hath come unto us, how opposite they are to the mind of God. They have no care for love, nor concerning the widow, nor concerning the orphan, nor concerning the afflicted, nor concerning him who is bound or loosed, nor concerning him who is hungry or thirsty. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>They refrain from the eucharist and from prayer, because they do not confess that the eucharist is the flesh of our Saviour Jesus Christ</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, which suffered for our sins, and which the Father of his goodness raised up.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
St Ignatius was ordained by St John the Evangelist, so he should know what the Gospel of John meant at 6:55, and he writes that those who do not confess the eucharist is the flesh of our Saviour Jesus Christ, as heretical opinions.  The confession of the Church, as Brian has pointed out, has always been the Eucharist is the Body and Blood of Our Lord, the novel doctrine of it being symbolic only came in the 1500's, and even then not all the reformers went that direction.  The Lutherans and Anglicans both believe that the Eucharist is the Body and Blood of Our Lord.<br>
Jeff the Finn<br>
